Data Dictionary

  • id: unique identifier for each observation.

  • valid_time: the date and time for which the weather data is valid (YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS).

  • latitude: north-south coordinate position of each observation.

  • longitude: east-west coordinate position.

  • tp: total precipitation, accumulated liquid and frozen water (rain, snow, etc.) that falls to the Earth's surface in metres (m).

  • u10: 10m U wind component - Eastward wind at 10 meters above surface (m/s). Wind observations vary on small space and time scales and are affected by the local terrain, vegetation and buildings. This parameter can be combined with the V component of 10m wind to give the speed and direction of the horizontal 10m wind.

  • v10: 10m V wind component - Northward wind at 10 meters above surface (m/s). Wind observations vary on small space and time scales and are affected by the local terrain, vegetation and buildings. This parameter can be combined with the U component of 10m wind to give the speed and direction of the horizontal 10m wind.

  • sp: Surface Pressure - Pressure at the Earth's surface in Pascals (Pa). Surface pressure is often used in combination with temperature to calculate air density.

  • u100: 100m V wind component - Eastward wind at 100 meters above surface (m/s).

  • v100: 100m V wind component - Northward wind at 100 meters above surface (m/s).

  • tcc: Total Cloud Cover - Proportion of the sky covered by clouds, fractions vary from 0 to 1.

  • ptype: Precipitation Type - Type of precipitation (categorical)

  • 0 = No precipitation

  • 1 = Rain

  • 3 = Freezing rain (i.e. supercooled raindrops which freeze on contact with the ground and other surfaces)

  • 5 = Snow

  • 6 = Wet snow (i.e. snow particles which are starting to melt)

  • 7 = Mixture of rain and snow

  • 8 = Ice pellets

  • 12 = Freezing drizzle

  • t2m: 2m Temperature - Temperature at 2 meters above surface, response variable in Kelvin (K)

We now examine the distribution of data in each column and the number of unique values for each. As seen from the plot below:

  • ID, latitude, longitude: - show discrete and even distribution, looks like a systematic grid-based spatial data organization.

  • tp: highly right-skewed distribution with most values near zero, expected for precipitation data as most locations have no or minimal rain at any given time.

  • Wind components (u10, v10, u100, v100): - all follow approximately normal distributions centered around zero, showing balanced eastward/westward and northward/southward wind movements. Pairs u10 and v10, as well as u100 and v100 distibutions look almost identical.

  • sp: - seems normally distributed, centered around 101000-102000 Pa.

  • tcc: - shows a distinctive bimodal distribution with peaks at 0 (clear skies) and 1 (completely overcast), meaning there is a tendency for cloud cover to be either minimal or extensive rather than partial.

  • ptype: - categorical data showing most observations fall into category 0 (no precipitation), with fewer instances of other precipitation types.

  • t2m: - follows a relatively normal distribution with most values clustered between 275-295K (2-22C), representing the typical UK temperature range.

Now we have the time values. As we can see these are currently in a form which our model would not be able to interpret. As this data spans one year, we have no need for this information, the month and day of the year are useful, for a macro and micro scale for annual timing, and while hour will be important for day/night temperature differences, clearly minutes and seconds are unnecessary/unhelpful.

# Convert day of month to day of year

def to_year_day(row):
    month = row['month']
    day_of_month = row['day_of_month']
    month_days = [31, 28, 31, 30, 31, 30, 31, 31, 30, 31, 30, 31]
    return int(np.sum(month_days[:month - 1]) + day_of_month)

training['day'] = training.apply(to_year_day, axis=1)

The next values are for surface pressure which we simply rescale using standard scaler. We see that this has a good correlation to temperature from both the plot of binned pressure values and the cross correlation values.

Then, we keep both u100 and v100 as they represent the wind velocity components. While we will keep these values and scale with standard scaler, we will also derive wind speed and direction as these correlate with temperature (northerly winds tend to bring colder arctic air while southernly bring hot equatorial air) later in our data engineering.

Total cloud cover is now our next column and this is simplified by already being in a 0-1 format that is perfect for our model. As such, we simply treat this with standard scaler and continue.

Finally for our existing data points, we have the precipitation type. For this, we are looking at sorting the data points in terms of atmospheric temperature required to form the precipitation. While the total list goes from 0-12, we see in our data there are only 7 unique values - due to IFS handling only rain and snow quantities. As such, we will resort this data as a new scale from 0-6 with 0 still corresponding to no rain and 1-6 a new scale of the original data.

IFS Precipitation Types:

  • 0 - No Precipitation
  • 1 - Rain
  • 3 - Freezing Rain
  • 5 - Snow
  • 6 - Wet Snow
  • 7 - Mixture of Rain and Snow
  • 8 - Ice Pellets
  • 12 - Freezing Drizzle

# Define a reordering function

def reorder_ptype(row):
    if row['ptype'] == 0:
        return 0
    elif row['ptype'] == 1:
        return 1
    elif row['ptype'] == 3:
        return 2
    elif row['ptype'] == 12: #While there is no occurence of freezing drizzle in our training data, it can appear in test data
        return 3
    elif row['ptype'] == 7:
        return 4
    elif row['ptype'] == 6:
        return 5
    elif row['ptype'] == 8:
        return 6
    elif row['ptype'] == 5:
        return 7
        

training['ordered_ptype'] = training.apply(reorder_ptype, axis=1)

def time_transformer(X):
    X['month'] = X['valid_time'].str.slice(5, 7).astype(int)
    X['day_of_month'] = X['valid_time'].str.slice(8, 10).astype(int)
    X['hour'] = X['valid_time'].str.slice(11, 13).astype(int) 

    def to_year_day(row):
        month = row['month']
        day_of_month = row['day_of_month']
        month_days = [31, 28, 31, 30, 31, 30, 31, 31, 30, 31, 30, 31]
        return int(np.sum(month_days[:month - 1]) + day_of_month)

    X['day'] = X.apply(to_year_day, axis=1)

    X['month_sin'] = np.sin(2 * np.pi * X['month']/12)
    X['month_cos'] = np.cos(2 * np.pi * X['month']/12)
    X['day_sin'] = np.sin(2 * np.pi * X['day']/365)
    X['day_cos'] = np.cos(2 * np.pi * X['day']/365)
    X['hour_sin'] = np.sin(2 * np.pi * X['hour']/24)
    X['hour_cos'] = np.cos(2 * np.pi * X['hour']/24)

    return X

def ordinal_ptype(X):
    def reorder_ptype(row):
        if row['ptype'] == 0:
            return 0
        elif row['ptype'] == 1:
            return 1
        elif row['ptype'] == 3:
            return 2
        elif row['ptype'] == 12: #While there is no occurence of freezing drizzle in our training data, it can appear in test data
            return 3
        elif row['ptype'] == 7:
            return 4
        elif row['ptype'] == 6:
            return 5
        elif row['ptype'] == 8:
            return 6
        elif row['ptype'] == 5:
            return 7

    X['ordered_ptype'] = X.apply(reorder_ptype, axis=1)

    return X

def wind_values(X):
    X['wind_speed'] = np.sqrt(X['u100']**2 + X['v100']**2)
    X['wind_direction'] = np.arctan2(X['v100'], X['u100']) # In radians

    X['wind_direction_sin'] = np.sin(X['wind_direction'])
    X['wind_direction_cos'] = np.cos(X['wind_direction'])

    return X

def historic_values(X):

    # Define locale
    def locale_sorter(row):
        return (8 + row['longitude'] - (row['longitude'] % 2)) / 2 + 6 * ((-50 + row['latitude'] - (row['latitude'] % 2)) / 2)

    X['locale'] = X.apply(locale_sorter, axis=1)

    X['local_wind_speed'] = X.groupby(['day', 'hour', 'locale'])['wind_speed'].transform('mean')

    X['local_precipitation'] = X.groupby(['day', 'hour', 'locale'])['tp'].transform('mean')

    X['absolute_hour'] = 24 * X['day'] + X['hour']

    # Create a shifted version of the X DataFrame
    X_shifted = X.copy()
    X_shifted['absolute_hour'] += 1  # Shift forward so current hour matches previous data
    X_shifted = X_shifted[['absolute_hour', 'locale', 'local_wind_speed', 'local_precipitation']]

    # Aggregate duplicates by taking mean of local_wind_speed and local_precipitation
    X_shifted = X_shifted.groupby(['absolute_hour', 'locale'], as_index=False).agg({
        'local_wind_speed': 'mean',
        'local_precipitation': 'mean'
    })

    X_shifted.rename(columns={'local_wind_speed': 'historic_local_wind_speed'}, inplace=True)
    X_shifted.rename(columns={'local_precipitation': 'historic_local_precipitation'}, inplace=True)

    # Merge the DataFrames on absolute_hour and locale
    X = X.merge(
        X_shifted,
        on=['absolute_hour', 'locale'],
        how='left'
    )

    return X

def clean_and_prep(X, columns_to_keep):

    # drop columns
    X = X[columns_to_keep]

    X = time_transformer(X)
    X = ordinal_ptype(X)
    X = wind_values(X)
    X = historic_values(X)

        # impute values
    X['historic_local_wind_speed'] = np.where(X['historic_local_wind_speed'].isna(), 
                        0, X['historic_local_wind_speed'])
    
    X['historic_local_precipitation'] = np.where(X['historic_local_precipitation'].isna(), 
                        0, X['historic_local_precipitation'])

    X = X.drop(columns=['valid_time', 'ptype', 'day_of_month', 'day', 'month', 'hour', 'wind_direction', 'locale', 'absolute_hour', 'local_wind_speed', 'local_precipitation'])

    return X

Modelling

KNN Regressor model

K-nearest neighborhood (KNN) regressor model leverages the spatial and temporal structure of weather data by finding the most similar data points in feature space via nearby locations, times and similar meteorological conditions. When predicting the temperature at a specific location and time, KNN model identifies the most relevant historical observations from nearby situations.

Since the dataset is very large (train around 10,6 million of observations) and given that we engineered additional features, including "nearby" ones, model training and tuning will be computationaly very expensive. To ease that process, we will apply Principal Component Analysis (PCA) dimension reduction technique to reduce dimensionality of data while preserving most of the important information.

Analyzing which features were preserved as a result of PCA dimensionality reduction, we can see that nearby features (historic local wind speed and historic local precipitation) are actually very important in explaining the temperature. historic local wind speed is top contributor in Principal component 1 (explaining 18.63% of variance) and historic local precipitation is #4 contributor in Principal component 3 (explaining 9.40% of variance). Overall, both nearby features in different components indicates they capture distinct aspects of weather patterns that are relevant to temperature prediction.

In[]:
# examine feature contributions to principal components
pca_components = pd.DataFrame(
    pca.components_,
    columns=X_train.columns
)

# absolute contribution of each feature to each component
component_loadings = pd.DataFrame(
    abs(pca.components_),
    columns=X_train.columns
)

# top features for each of the first few components
num_components_to_show = min(5, reduced_dims)  
for i in range(num_components_to_show):
    explained_var = pca.explained_variance_ratio_[i] * 100
    print(f"Principal Component {i+1} (explains {explained_var:.2f}% of variance)")
    
    # sort features by importance 
    top_features = component_loadings.iloc[i].sort_values(ascending=False)
    print(top_features[:5].to_string())  
    print("\n")

# examine how nearby features are preserved
nearby_features = [col for col in X_train.columns if 'historic_local' in col or 'nearby' in col]
if nearby_features:
    nearby_importance = pd.DataFrame(index=nearby_features)
    
    # total contribution of each nearby feature across components
    for feature in nearby_features:
        importance_scores = []
        for i in range(reduced_dims):
            importance = abs(pca_components.loc[i, feature]) * pca.explained_variance_ratio_[i]
            importance_scores.append(importance)
        nearby_importance.loc[feature, 'Total Weighted Importance'] = sum(importance_scores)
    
    print("Importance of nearby features across all principal components:")
    print(nearby_importance.sort_values('Total Weighted Importance', ascending=False))

We fitted and trained KNN model using initial parameters:

  • n_neighbors=5 means model uses 5 closest weather conditions to make a prediction, 5 is a balance between enough similarity while avoiding excessive smoothing.
  • weights='distance' means that model weighs closer neighbors more importantly than distant ones, which makes sense for the temperature prediction.
  • algorithm='auto' allows to select more efficient algorithm.
  • leaf_size=30 is the speed of construction and query for neighbors searches and 30 often used as a default value.
  • n_jobs=-1 means model uses all available CPU for computation, which makes sense given that dataset is large.

The model performance on the training data is RMSE = 0.0000 and RMSE = 0.5139 on validation data. That means:

  1. our model is overfitting - it memorizes the training set perfectly rather than learning generalizable patterns. We will use different weights at tuning our model, try different numbers of neighbors, or various leaf sizes to improve the performance.
  2. Despite the overfitting, RMSE of 0.5139 is relatively small for temperature prediction, suggesting the model still may be generalizing reasonably to new data.

We will create a sample of 5% of our train data to reduce computational cost of tuning / searching for best parameters.

  • n_neighbors: testing 3, 5, and 7 neighbors to find the optimal size
  • leaf_size: testing 10 and 20
  • p: testing distance metrics - 1 is Manhattan distance and 2 is Euclidean distance.

GridSearchCV tests all parameter combinations (12 total) using:

  • 2-fold cross-validation (cv=2)
  • neg_mean_squared_error as the key metric
  • parallel processing (n_jobs=2)
  • distance weight (kept constant)

As a result, our best parameters are:

  • leaf_size=10:
  • n_neighbors=5
  • p=2 Euclidean distance works best

So, as a result of the fine-tuning we fitted and trained model with best parameters, that appeared to be almost equal to the initial default ones. Basically, the only thing that changed was leaf_size = 10 instead of 30. Hence, model's performance did not change comparing before the tuning. Most probably, KNN was already robust enough for this prediction task so that it was less sensitive for parameters tuning, also perhaps, our intuition for selecting parameters was confirmed, such as for selecting weight=distance, which was sensible given the data structure. Also, we fed KNN with nearby features, which the model would do by default, with given nearby features we basically set the priorities for the model. Even though, there is no straightforward way to extract which features were most important for KNN models prediction, our PCA confirmed that nearby features were valuable contributors. KNNs trained on best hyperparameters achieved RMSE 0.5139 on validation and 0.5140 on test dataset, indicating strong predictive performance despite some overfitting. This means that this model predicts temperatures with average error of just 0.5139 of Kelvin unit, which is pretty accurate.

Otherwise, we could potentially try training model without dimensionality reduction, trying more number of parameters - but both cases are too computationally expensive and not feasible for our computer. We will fit other models to see if alternatives can perform well without overfitting.

Random Forest Regressor

We chose a Random Forest Regressor, an ensemble method that averages the outputs of multiple decision trees.

This approach is particularly well-suited to our system, as it effectively handles complex, non-linear relationships between environmental features while minimizing the impact of less informative variables. Although individual trees are prone to overfitting, combining their outputs significantly reduces this risk as is seen by this model's low RMSE value.

Now we generate a single random Forest and assess its performanceas a trial run. This Forest is large and will have the following hyperparameters:

  • max_features = 1 (this limits each split to a single feature)
  • min_samples_leaf = 1 (this means we are allowing for very small leafs - risks overfitting)
  • min_samples_split = 2 (this means we are allowing very specific differentiation which will result in longer run times)
  • max_depth = None (this means each tree will continue to grow until fully expanded - can increase runtime but improves the level of tree diversity)
  • max_features = 1 (By having this small value our trees are more diverse and random - this reduces risk of tree rendundancy but necessitates a larger forest)
  • n_estimator = 100 (The number of trees in the forest)

Here we again see a very low rmse value relative to the median temperature. This suggests that the splitting of the dataset was imperfect as the model appears to still be quite overfit.

This is because the original data set is dense in time and space, this means that for any point we have removed, we still have nearby spacial and temporal values for temperature. Thus, it appears that our model is currently tightly fit to the 2018 weather data and that our tuning is likely to further this. However, we still elect to proceed and we will analyse the reality of this later when we have applied a model to the test set.

XGBoost

We chose XGBoost for predicting temperature on this high-resolution weather dataset due to its strong performance with structured data and ability to capture complex nonlinear relationships. XGBoost supports regularization to reduce overfitting, and scales well with large datasets both of which make it well-suited for the granular, feature-rich nature of weather data. Its flexibility and speed also make it ideal for efficient hyperparameter tuning and iterative experimentation.

In[75]:
# Define the parameter distributions

param_distributions = {
    'n_estimators': randint(200, 300),   # number of trees (boosting rounds) - more improve performance, and computation time
    'max_depth': randint(2, 4),   # max depths of each tree - deeper tress capture more complex patterns, but can overfit
    'learning_rate': uniform(0.01, 0.3),   # controls how much the model adjusts after each tree - lower values can lead to better generalisation but need more trees
    'subsample': uniform(0.6, 1),   # the fraction of the data to use for fitting each tree - helps prevent overfitting 
    'reg_alpha': uniform(0.1, 0.3),  # L1 regularization to prevent overfitting 
    'reg_lambda': uniform(0, 0.5) # L2 regularization to prevent overfitting 
}
In[76]:
# Set up xgb 

xgb = XGBRegressor(
    random_state=5059,
    n_jobs=1,   # use only 1 thread
    eval_metric='rmse'
)
In[81]:
# Create RandomizedSearchCV object

# will test a specified number of random combos of hyperparameters in the param_distributions

random_search = RandomizedSearchCV(
    estimator=xgb,
    param_distributions=param_distributions,
    n_iter=30, 
    scoring='neg_root_mean_squared_error',
    cv=3,
    verbose=3,
    n_jobs=2,
    random_state=5059
)

This will randomly sample 30 different combinations of hyperparameters from the specified param_distributions dictionary. For each combination, it will train the model using 3-fold cross-validation, scoring each run using negative RMSE (since scikit-learn minimizes score by default).

Arguments:

  • estimator: the base XGBoost model (XGBRegressor) that we want to tune.
  • param_distributions: dictionary defining the ranges/distributions from which hyperparameters will be randomly sampled.
  • n_iter: number of random hyperparameter combinations to try (higher = more thorough search).
  • scoring: the metric used to evaluate model performance during tuning. Here, we're using negative root mean squared error (neg_root_mean_squared_error), because lower RMSE = better.
  • cv: number of folds in cross-validation (3-fold means the data is split into 3 subsets; the model is trained on 2 and validated on the 3rd, repeated 3 times with different splits).
  • verbose: controls how much output is shown during fitting (3 = detailed progress).
  • n_jobs: number of parallel jobs to run (2 = use 2 CPU cores; -1 would use all available).
  • random_state: ensures reproducibility of the random sampling for consistent results.

# Investigate why training CV RMSE is higher than validation RMSE by comparing the feature distributions between the training and validation sets 
# to detect any distribution shift, data leakage, or imbalance that might make the validation set easier to predict

for col in training_cleaned.columns:
    sns.kdeplot(training_cleaned[col], label='Train')

    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

The observed results of this XGBoost model - where the training cross-validation (CV) RMSE is significantly higher than the validation RMSE - are likely due to a data leakage issue introduced by the way the validation set was constructed. The dataset is time-ordered, but we chose to use every 5th data point to construct the validation set, causing the training and validation sets to be interleaved. This inadvertently allows the model to train on data that is immediately adjacent in time to the validation points (this data is also very high-resolutin data), providing it with information that would not be available in a real-world forecasting scenario. As a result, the model performs unusually well on the validation set, leading to an artificially low RMSE. In contrast, the cross-validation within the training data preserves temporal separation between folds, making it a more honest reflection of the models true generalization performance, hence the higher RMSE. This discrepancy highlights the importance of preserving temporal integrity in train/validation splits for time-dependent data. It could have been better to hold out a contiguous block from the end of the dataset as validation, letting us predict only on future data, and using only past data to train exactly what you'd want in production. However, we only had a year of data, and leaving out a chunk at the end, like December, for example, would mean we did not expose our model to a full cycle of weather patterns. We were also constrained in this specific project by not being able to shuffle, as we were working across software programmmes and would not have been able to transfer a random seed. So, all this taken into account, we have taken the decision not to use XGBoost for our predictions, and instead go forward with either KNN or Random Forest, which seem to be more robust to this validation set issue.

This can save significant processing time.

Hyperparameters

In[]:
import inspect;

# Extract constructor from Net
from neural_net.net import Net;
empty_net = Net(num_X_features, "empty");
net_constructor = empty_net.__init__;

# Extract default values from constructor
default_args = inspect.signature(net_constructor); 

# Print default values
print(default_args);

These are non-architectural hyperparameters that generally remain consistent between model architectures (with limited exceptions, e.g. gradient descent on the simpler model). Some hyperparameters are arbitrary constants chosen through inspection of training outputs, e.g. early stopping tolerance, while others define the optimisation method to choose an optimal hyperparameter, e.g. lr_start.

Batch size: number of samples processed before the model's parameters are updated. A large batch size helps smooth out gradient estimates and can improve throughput on modern GPUs with large memory capacities. I trained these models on a GTX 3080 Ti which meant I could use a large batch size. Although I trained this model on a powerful GPU, I had a very weak CPU which slowed down the training process considerably.

Epochs: maximum number of iterations of backpropagation. Early stopping meant this number of iterations was never reachedtypically training stopped around ~15 iterations.

Output size: one neuron because we're producing a single prediction.

Optimiser: Regular gradient descent consistently produces constant improvements in loss, but spends too long in high-loss regions during testing. Adam is an optimiser that uses adaptive estimates of first and second moments, which reaches the low-loss region within 23 epochs but can't improve on these estimates further. AdaBound is an optimiser that uses Adam during the initial epochs to arrive at the low-loss regions, then gradually transitions its adaptive bounds toward those of stochastic gradient descent to produce steady improvements once in the low-loss area.

Adabound Gamma: the gamma parameter controls how quickly the adaptive learning-rate bounds widen during training. A smaller gamma keeps the bounds narrow for longercloser to Adams behaviourwhile a larger gamma allows a faster transition toward stochastic gradient descent, helping fine-grained convergence.

Criterion (Loss function): Mean Squared Error (MSE) measures the average of the squares of the errors between predictions and targets. It's widely used in regression tasks because it heavily penalises larger errors, encouraging the model to focus on reducing outliers.

lr_start: method of determining the starting learning rate. "range" means we use a learning-rate range test during the first epochcycling through a set of candidate ratesand then choose the rate which produced the greatest decrease in loss as the initial learning rate for subsequent training.

lr_scheduler (Plateau): this scheduler, often implemented as ReduceLROnPlateau, monitors a validation metric (e.g. validation loss) and reduces the learning rate by a given factor when no improvement is observed for a specified number of epochs. It helps the optimizer navigate plateaus in the loss landscape by taking smaller steps when approaching a minimum.

use_clipping: if True, gradients are clipped to a maximum norm before each update to prevent exploding gradients. This ensures that updates remain stable, especially in deep networks or when using high learning rates.

lr_factor: the factor by which the learning rate is multiplied when the scheduler triggers. A factor of 1 means no change, while a value less than 1 reduces the learning rate (e.g. 0.1 makes it ten times smaller).

normalise_y: when True, the target variable is scaled to zero mean and unit variance before training, and rescaled back when making predictions. Normalising targets stabilises and accelerates convergence, especially when the targets scale differs significantly from input features.

early_stopping_tolerance: the minimum relative improvement in the monitored metric (e.g. validation loss) to qualify as an actual improvement. If the change in loss between epochs is less than this tolerance, it's considered as no improvement.

early_stopping_patience: the number of consecutive epochs for which the monitored metric can fail to improve beyond the tolerance before training is halted early. This prevents overfitting and saves computation once the model stops making meaningful progress.

Network Architecture

Simple Linear Net
In[]:
from neural_net.net_arch import SimpleLinearNet
simple_linear_net = SimpleLinearNet(num_X_features);
simple_linear_net.load();

simple_linear_net.get_info();

One neuron for each of our 19 features, all connecting to a single output neuron with a linear activation function.

We can inspect the weights and biases of this simple model to determine which features the model finds important.

In[]:
# Get output layer info from model
output_layer = simple_linear_net.get_final_layer(print_to_terminal = False);
simple_linear_net_weights = output_layer["_SimpleLinearNet__output_linear.weight"];

# Combine output layer and features
feature_weights = dict(zip(X_features, simple_linear_net_weights));

# Sort feature and weights map by absolute weight
feature_weights = {
    feature: weight 
    for feature, weight in sorted(feature_weights.items(), key = lambda w: abs(w[1]), reverse = True)
}

# Print
for feature, weight in feature_weights.items():
    print(f"Feature: {feature}, weight: {weight}");

Even this simple model has broadly agreed with our feature exploration - seasonal variations are by far the most important, followed by latitude, then wind vector and precipitation type whilst the others are relatively meaningless.

There are a few discrepancies: longitude and wind direction aren't as important as they should be, because these are more complex relationships (e.g. longitude isn't significant by itself but needs to be combined with latitude to infer altitude, which is important).

In[]:
simple_linear_net.evaluate(testing, target_testing);

The model stopped training due to early stopping after four epochs, yet the loss curve doesn't look like it's approaching a minima yet. The early stopping scheme stops training too soon, as the model could learn more patterns without overfitting to noise. Four is the size of the early stopping window by default and is the minimum number of epochs that the model can go through. Therefore, early stopping is stopping training at the first chance it gets. This problem appears in all models, but retraining all models with a lower early stopping threshold is too computationally expensive.

The learning rate scheduler successfully recognises a plateau in loss reduction and decreases the learning rate to increase loss reduction, but early stopping means the model is not allowed to explore different weights and biases at this lower learning rate. Making early stopping less aggressive or enabling communication between the early stopping and the scheduler (e.g. prevent early stopping if learning rate has dropped) would address this.

This model appears to overpredict temperature (more points on left than right hand side of dotted line), and the model struggles at higher temperatures and tends to predict some mean high temperature instead. Adding model complexity should enable the model to address these flaws.

Single Layer Net
In[]:
from neural_net.net_arch import SingleLayerNet
single_relu_net = SingleLayerNet(num_X_features);
single_relu_net.load();

single_relu_net.get_info();

Single linear net: our 19 features goes into a hidden layer of 16 neurons, which then combine to produce our output (19 -> 16 -> 1).

There is some evidence here to indicate that a more complex model would be better. Because the training data was standardised in its entirety (both independent and dependent variables), the average weight of each neuron should be between -1 and 1 (e.g. like the simple linear net). These neuron weights are high, indicating that they're doing "too much" and would benefit from an additional layer to offload the complexity to.

In[]:
print(single_relu_net._SingleLayerNet__relu);
print("\n");

print(inspect.getsource(single_relu_net.forward));

We use a variant of the non-linear ReLU activation function between the hidden layer and the output layer to capture non-linearities. This "leaky" variant is one way of combatting neuron death.

ReLU outputs the input directly if it's positive and outputs zero if it's negative. This can lead to "dying ReLU" where neurons become inactive if they consistently receive negative inputs, as the gradient becomes zero. Leaky ReLU addresses this issue by allowing a small, non-zero gradient for negative inputs. Instead of outputting zero for negative inputs, it outputs a small, negative value (in our case, 0.01 * x).

In[]:
single_relu_net.evaluate(testing, target_testing);

As expected, the more complex model outperformed the simpler linear net because it captured more complex relationships.

As with the previous model, the early stopping kicks in too soon here. The learning rate scheduler encounters the same issues also, except the scheduler is never given the chance to drop the learning rate before early stopping takes effect.

Three layer net
In[]:
from neural_net.net_arch import ThreeLayerNet;
three_relu_net = ThreeLayerNet(num_X_features);
three_relu_net.load();

three_relu_net.get_info();

This net has a 19 -> 128 -> 64 -> 32 -> 1 structure.

These weights have more reasonable values, with the exception of small excesses in the output layer. Given the gains in RMSE from increasing the number of layers, adding one more step in complexity should produce the best model.

In[]:
three_relu_net.evaluate(testing, target_testing);

Outperformed single-layer as expected.

As before, the model suffers from early stopping and learning rate scheduler issues.

The model now doesn't exhibit any biases, and strange outlier predictions that existed with previous models don't appear here.
